+## Current strengths
+
+1. Acceptance is no longer prompt-only; it is a runtime object model and evaluator.
+2. Goal alignment is explicit via `success_criteria` and per-criterion checks.
+3. Contract inference now better separates primary success criteria, constraints, prohibited actions, and explicit-path deliverables for multi-part prompts.
+4. Criterion evaluation now prefers primary bound executable evidence over transcript-only wording, which reduces false passes when artifact checks fail.
+5. Some artifact-level validation is already available through executable checks, including inferred directory/file-glob/JSON-field existence cases.
+6. Overclaiming is reduced by parent-finalizer wording control.
+7. Reports are persisted and visible through status surfaces.
+
+## Current limitations
+
+1. Contract inference is still heuristic, even after the latest multi-part prompt improvements.
+2. Criterion matching is stronger but still mostly deterministic lexical/structural normalization rather than a full semantic judge.
+3. Executable checks are broader now, but still not enough for all artifact/result shapes.
+4. `final_assessment` is readable text, but not yet a richer machine-oriented summary schema.
+5. The broad full-suite runtime around `tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py` can be heavy, so targeted acceptance regression slices are currently the practical verification path.
+
+## Recommended next phases
+
+### Phase A: stronger contract inference
+
+Objective:
+- infer better success criteria, constraints, deliverables, and prohibited actions for multi-part tasks
+
+Ideas:
+- improve split/normalization rules
+- better path/artifact extraction
+- stronger mapping from user wording to criterion-bound checks
+- distinguish primary deliverable vs supporting requirements
+
+Success signal:
+- fewer under-specified contracts for realistic multi-requirement prompts
+
+### Phase B: stronger criterion binding and semantic coverage
+
+Objective:
+- reduce false inconclusive/pass results caused by shallow text overlap
+
+Ideas:
+- richer criterion tokenization/normalization
+- explicit artifact/result binding metadata
+- optional lightweight semantic judge only for unresolved borderline cases
+
+Success signal:
+- per-criterion pass/fail aligns better with real user intent rather than exact wording overlap
+
+### Phase C: broader executable checks
+
+Objective:
+- strengthen evidence quality for concrete deliverables
+
+Ideas:
+- directory assertions
+- file glob assertions
+- structured diff assertions
+- JSON schema/value assertions beyond single field match
+- command exit-code + stdout/stderr compound assertions
+
+Success signal:
+- more task types can be accepted on artifacts/results instead of transcript wording
+
+### Phase D: richer acceptance schema and UX
+
+Objective:
+- make acceptance easier to consume by humans and other runtime components
+
+Ideas:
+- add structured summary fields for passed/unmet/violated/evidence sections
+- expose compact/latest acceptance more broadly in status/resume surfaces
+- add optional history browsing command later if needed
+
+Success signal:
+- easier debugging, easier operator review, easier downstream gating
+
+### Phase E: stricter gate policies when confidence is high
+
+Objective:
+- selectively move from advisory toward stronger gating for tasks with high-quality executable checks
+
+Ideas:
+- strict mode defaults only when contract/check quality is high
+- allow repo/task-specific gating policies
+- distinguish reversible advisory tasks from must-verify tasks
+
+Success signal:
+- stronger trust in completion claims without making heuristic-only tasks too brittle
+
+## Recommended immediate next step
+
+The best next implementation step is Phase A + part of Phase C:
+- improve contract inference for multi-part goals
+- expand criterion/prohibited-action binding to inferred executable checks
+
+Reason:
+- the current architecture is already in place
+- the biggest remaining gap for true goal alignment is not persistence or UI, but how accurately the inferred contract captures the user's real success conditions
+
+## Short operational summary
+
+Hermes already has a real acceptance framework.
+
+Today it works as:
+- infer task contract
+- run deterministic acceptance checks
+- produce a structured acceptance result
+- soften/block overclaiming in parent finalization
+- persist latest acceptance report
+- expose it in status views
+
+The main remaining problem is not whether a framework exists, but how strong and task-accurate the inferred contract and checks are.
