+# Hermes Acceptance Upgrade Roadmap
+
+> For Hermes: Use subagent-driven-development skill to implement this roadmap batch-by-batch.
+
+Date: 2026-04-21
+Repo: `~/.hermes/hermes-agent`
+
+Goal: Evolve Hermes acceptance from a solid anti-overclaim guardrail into a stronger task-alignment verification system that more reliably checks whether delivered results actually satisfy user goals.
+
+Architecture: Preserve the current runtime acceptance chain (`TaskContract` -> `VerificationCheck` -> `CheckResult` -> `AcceptanceResult` -> parent finalizer -> persistence/status) and improve it in layers. Prioritize correctness of inferred contracts first, then criterion-level satisfaction quality, then executable evidence breadth, then richer structured reporting, and finally confidence-aware gate policies.
+
+Tech Stack: Python, deterministic inference/evaluation heuristics in `agent/acceptance.py`, parent-finalizer integration in `run_agent.py`, persistence in `hermes_state.py`, status surfaces in `cli.py` and `gateway/run.py`, pytest via `uv run --extra dev pytest`.
+
+---
+
+## Core judgment
+
+The current framework already exists and is real runtime behavior, not just design intent. It currently does these things well:
+- infers a machine-readable task contract from the user request
+- evaluates transcript coverage, prohibited actions, and deterministic executable checks
+- prevents or softens overclaiming in the parent finalizer
+- persists acceptance reports and exposes latest acceptance through status surfaces
+
+The main remaining problem is no longer "do we have acceptance?" but "how accurately does acceptance represent and verify the real task goal?"
+
+---
+
+## Current baseline
+
+Verified from the repo:
+- Design snapshot exists in `docs/acceptance-framework-design.md`
+- Contract/evaluator live in `agent/acceptance.py`
+- Parent finalizer integration lives in `run_agent.py`
+- Acceptance persistence lives in `hermes_state.py`
+- Tests already cover acceptance evaluator, parent finalizer, and persistence:
+  - `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+  - `tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py`
+  - `tests/test_hermes_state_acceptance.py`
+
+Current strengths:
+1. Acceptance runs before final return.
+2. Per-criterion results already exist.
+3. Bound executable evidence is already possible for some criteria.
+4. Prohibited actions are already part of evaluation.
+5. Reports are persisted and visible.
+
+Current top weaknesses:
+1. Contract inference is still heuristic and may under-specify real goals.
+2. Criterion satisfaction is still too lexical/structural in borderline cases.
+3. Executable checks are still a narrow library.
+4. Acceptance summary is readable but not yet rich enough for downstream automation/recovery.
+5. Gate policy is coarse relative to evidence quality.
+
+---
+
+## Roadmap priorities
+
+Priority order:
+- P1: stronger contract inference
+- P2: stronger criterion satisfaction / semantic-ish coverage
+- P3: broader deterministic executable checks
+- P4: richer structured acceptance summary + operator diagnostics
+- P5: confidence-aware gate policies
+
+Why this order:
+- Every downstream acceptance decision depends on contract quality.
+- Better criterion matching matters only after the right criteria exist.
+- Stronger executable evidence is most valuable once criteria are correctly inferred and bound.
+- Reporting and gates should improve after evidence quality improves.
+
+---
+
+## Batch 1 (highest priority): stronger contract inference
+
+Objective: Make inferred `TaskContract`s closer to the user’s real success conditions for multi-part tasks.
+
+Primary files:
+- Modify: `agent/acceptance.py`
+- Modify: `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+- Reference: `docs/acceptance-framework-design.md`
+
+Problems to solve:
+- multi-part tasks may produce noisy or incomplete `success_criteria`
+- `deliverable` may still mirror the raw prompt instead of the real artifact/result
+- constraints and prohibited actions are only partially distinguished from positive goals
+- inferred executable checks are still too narrow/fragile
+
+Implementation focus:
+1. Improve success-criteria normalization and deduplication.
+2. Better distinguish:
+   - primary deliverable
+   - supporting success requirements
+   - constraints
+   - prohibited actions
+3. Improve explicit path/artifact extraction.
+4. Infer criterion-bound executable checks more accurately when the text clearly implies them.
+
+Target tests:
+- `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py` inference-only tests
+- then full `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+- then targeted parent-finalizer regression slice in `tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py`
+
+Status:
+- This batch already has a dedicated plan and appears implemented/planned in `docs/plans/2026-04-21-contract-inference-upgrade-implementation-plan.md`.
+- Treat this as foundational and complete/verify before deeper semantic upgrades.
+
+Success signal:
+- realistic multi-requirement prompts produce cleaner and more useful contracts
+- fewer missing or misclassified criteria
+
+---
+
+## Batch 2: stronger per-criterion satisfaction and wording-variation robustness
+
+Objective: Reduce false inconclusive/pass outcomes caused by shallow wording overlap.
+
+Primary files:
+- Modify: `agent/acceptance.py`
+- Modify: `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+- Reference: `docs/acceptance-framework-design.md`
+
+Problems to solve:
+- meaning-preserving wording changes can still fail criterion coverage
+- some criteria may still look satisfied from transcript wording without strong result evidence
+- lexical matching is too brittle for user-goal alignment in edge cases
+
+Implementation focus:
+1. Stronger normalization/tokenization for criterion matching.
+2. Limited synonym/canonicalization support where domain-safe.
+3. Prefer criterion-bound executable evidence over weak transcript mismatch.
+4. Keep this deterministic; do not add default LLM-as-judge in this batch.
+5. If needed later, reserve a very narrow semantic fallback only for unresolved borderline cases.
+
+Target tests:
+- wording-variation acceptance tests
+- criterion-pass-from-bound-check tests
+- mixed transcript/evidence edge cases
+- then full `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+- then targeted `tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py` acceptance slice
+
+Status:
+- This batch already has a dedicated plan in `docs/plans/2026-04-21-acceptance-semantic-coverage-and-rich-checks-plan.md`.
+- It should be the next default implementation stream after Batch 1 validation.
+
+Success signal:
+- criterion pass/fail aligns better with actual result satisfaction rather than literal wording overlap
+
+---
+
+## Batch 3: broaden deterministic executable checks
+
+Objective: Increase the proportion of tasks that can be accepted on concrete result evidence instead of transcript claims.
+
+Primary files:
+- Modify: `agent/acceptance.py`
+- Modify: `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+- Reference: `tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py`
+
+Highest-value new check kinds:
+1. `directory_exists`
+2. `file_glob_count`
+3. `json_field_exists`
+4. `json_field_contains`
+5. `command_stdout_regex` or equivalent compound command assertion
+
+Second-wave candidates:
+6. richer JSON equality/set assertions
+7. diff-oriented assertions for edited files/configs
+8. optional lightweight service/runtime checks where safe and deterministic
+
+Design constraints:
+- keep checks local and deterministic
+- avoid broad arbitrary re-execution of tool histories
+- prefer a small library of high-value checks over speculative abstraction
+
+Target tests:
+- one fail-first test per new check kind
+- success + failure path for each check kind
+- criterion-bound evidence integration where relevant
+- targeted parent-finalizer regression after each cluster
+
+Status:
+- part of this already appears in the semantic/rich-checks plan, but this roadmap clarifies the intended priority order within the check-expansion work.
+
+Success signal:
+- more artifact/result-oriented tasks can be accepted with hard evidence
+- fewer acceptance decisions rely mainly on assistant phrasing
+
+---
+
+## Batch 4: richer acceptance result schema and operator diagnostics
+
+Objective: Make acceptance outputs more useful for downstream logic, debugging, and recovery.
+
+Primary files:
+- Modify: `agent/acceptance.py`
+- Modify: `run_agent.py`
+- Modify: `hermes_state.py` only if schema changes become necessary
+- Modify: status readers in `cli.py` and `gateway/run.py` if new fields are surfaced
+- Modify/add tests accordingly
+
+Problems to solve:
+- `final_assessment` is readable but still mostly summary text
+- it is harder than necessary to answer:
+  - which criteria passed?
+  - which evidence satisfied them?
+  - what is the smallest next step to move inconclusive -> pass?
+
+Implementation focus:
+1. Add richer structured summary fields while preserving compatibility.
+2. Add explicit criterion-to-evidence mapping.
+3. Improve compact operator-facing diagnostics in latest acceptance surfaces.
+4. Keep text summary readable while adding machine-usable structure.
+
+Possible structured additions:
+- `passed_criteria`
+- `violated_prohibited_actions`
+- `evidence_by_criterion`
+- `failed_check_ids`
+- `inconclusive_check_ids`
+- `evidence_strength` or similar
+
+Target tests:
+- acceptance serialization tests
+- persistence tests in `tests/test_hermes_state_acceptance.py`
+- status output tests for latest acceptance display
+
+Success signal:
+- acceptance reports become better inputs for debugging, recovery, and future automation
+
+---
+
+## Batch 5: confidence-aware gate policy
+
+Objective: Make completion-wording enforcement reflect evidence quality rather than one coarse global mode.
+
+Primary files:
+- Modify: `run_agent.py`
+- Modify: `agent/acceptance.py`
+- Modify tests in `tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py` and `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`
+
+Problems to solve:
+- easy-to-verify tasks and hard-to-verify tasks currently share coarse modes (`advisory` / `warn` / `strict`)
+- heuristic-only tasks should not be treated exactly like artifact-verified tasks
+- strongly verified tasks should support stronger completion confidence
+
+Implementation focus:
+1. Derive a lightweight confidence/evidence-strength signal from acceptance results.
+2. Let gate behavior depend partly on evidence quality.
+3. Preserve manual mode overrides.
+4. Keep user-visible wording clear: e.g. distinguish “done” vs “verified done”.
+
+Target tests:
+- parent-finalizer wording tests under different evidence strengths
+- regression tests that preserve current default behavior where no stronger signal exists
+
+Success signal:
+- stronger trust where hard evidence exists
+- fewer brittle overreactions where only heuristic evidence is possible
+
+---
+
+## Recommended execution sequence
+
+Default order for implementation from this point:
+1. Validate/finish Batch 1 (contract inference foundation).
+2. Execute Batch 2 Task 1 first (criterion normalization / wording-variation coverage).
+3. Continue Batch 2 with bound-evidence priority improvements.
+4. Expand Batch 3 checks in this order:
+   - `directory_exists`
+   - `file_glob_count`
+   - `json_field_exists`
+   - `json_field_contains`
+   - compound command stdout assertion
+5. Move to Batch 4 structured reporting.
+6. Move to Batch 5 evidence-aware gate policy.
+
+Reason:
+- correctness pipeline = contract quality -> criterion satisfaction quality -> result evidence breadth -> reporting -> gate behavior
+
+---
+
+## Verification contract for the roadmap
+
+For every batch:
+1. Use strict TDD for behavior changes.
+2. Add the narrowest failing tests first.
+3. Run targeted tests to RED.
+4. Implement minimal code to GREEN.
+5. Re-run full relevant file tests.
+6. Re-run targeted parent-finalizer regression slice before closing the batch.
+7. Update `docs/acceptance-framework-design.md` when the runtime design materially changes.
+
+Suggested recurring commands:
+- `uv run --extra dev pytest tests/agent/test_acceptance.py -n 0 -q`
+- `uv run --extra dev pytest tests/agent/test_acceptance.py tests/run_agent/test_run_agent.py -n 0 -k 'acceptance or parent_finalizer' -q`
+- `uv run --extra dev pytest tests/test_hermes_state_acceptance.py -n 0 -q`
+
+---
+
+## Risks and guardrails
+
+Main risks:
+1. Over-permissive criterion normalization causing false passes.
+2. Too many new check kinds creating noisy or unstable reports.
+3. Structured-report upgrades causing unnecessary schema churn.
+4. Gate-policy tightening becoming brittle before evidence quality is high enough.
+
+Guardrails:
+- change one verification dimension at a time
+- prefer reversible helper-level changes
+- keep schema stable unless a richer structure clearly pays for itself
+- do not tighten gate behavior before evidence quality improves
+
+---
+
+## Short operational summary
+
+Hermes already has an acceptance framework.
+The right next move is not to reinvent it, but to strengthen it in this order:
+1. infer the right task contract
+2. judge criteria more by result meaning/evidence than by wording overlap
+3. expand deterministic checks for real artifacts and outputs
+4. make reports richer and more operational
+5. only then make gates smarter/stricter
+
+This roadmap is the umbrella over the already-created Batch 1 and Batch 2 plans and sets the default implementation order from here.
