+# Hermes Contract Inference Upgrade Implementation Plan
+
+> For Hermes: Use subagent-driven-development skill to implement this plan task-by-task.
+
+Date: 2026-04-21
+Repo: `~/.hermes/hermes-agent`
+
+Goal: Upgrade Hermes acceptance contract inference so inferred `TaskContract`s more accurately reflect multi-part user goals, explicit artifact requirements, and prohibited actions, while preserving the current deterministic MVP acceptance architecture.
+
+Architecture: Keep the existing `agent/acceptance.py` inference/evaluation boundary, but strengthen inference in three places: criterion extraction, deliverable/constraint/prohibited-action extraction, and inferred executable-check generation. Drive the work with strict TDD in `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`, adding narrow inference-only tests before changing implementation. Preserve parent-finalizer integration by keeping the output shape (`TaskContract`, `VerificationCheck`) stable.
+
+Tech Stack: Python, regex/string normalization heuristics, existing acceptance evaluator in `agent/acceptance.py`, pytest via `uv run --extra dev pytest`.
+
+---
+
+## Current Baseline
+
+Verified in the current codebase:
+
+- `infer_minimal_task_contract(...)` lives in `agent/acceptance.py:75-119`.
+- Current contract inference is mainly driven by:
+  - `_infer_success_criteria(...)`
+  - `_extract_prohibited_actions(...)`
+  - `_extract_explicit_path(...)`
+  - `_infer_output_checks(...)`
+  - `_infer_prohibited_action_checks(...)`
+- `task_summary` and `deliverable` both default to the truncated raw user text.
+- Success-criteria splitting is currently shallow: comma/semicolon/`且`/`并且` split with minimal normalization.
+- Prohibited-action extraction currently focuses on `不要...` patterns.
+- Inferred executable checks currently cover only a narrow set of path/content/output cases.
+- Existing inference test coverage is minimal: `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py::test_infer_minimal_task_contract_adds_mvp_checks` verifies only baseline checks and non-empty criteria.
+
+## Problem Statement
+
+The acceptance framework exists, but the biggest remaining weakness is contract quality:
+
+1. multi-part prompts can produce under-specified or noisy `success_criteria`
+2. `deliverable` is not distinguished from the full raw request
+3. supporting constraints and prohibited actions are only partially extracted
+4. inferred executable checks are too narrow for realistic file/artifact-oriented tasks
+5. poor inferred contracts weaken downstream acceptance even when evaluator logic is sound
+
+## Success Criteria
+
+1. Multi-part prompts infer cleaner, deduplicated `success_criteria` that separate primary requirements from negative constraints.
+2. Explicit artifact/path requirements produce criterion-bound inferred executable checks when the text clearly implies them.
+3. `prohibited_actions` extraction covers common Chinese and English negative-instruction patterns beyond just `不要...`.
+4. `deliverable` is more specific than the raw full prompt when an explicit artifact/result can be inferred.
+5. Existing acceptance evaluation behavior remains compatible because `TaskContract` and `VerificationCheck` schemas stay unchanged.
+6. New inference behaviors are covered by narrow pytest tests that fail first and then pass.
+
+## Constraints
+
+- Keep inference deterministic; do not add an LLM-based inference pass.
+- Keep the public dataclass schema stable.
+- Do not redesign the acceptance evaluator in this phase.
+- Prefer small, composable helper functions over one large inference function.
+- Preserve backward compatibility for existing acceptance tests unless they intentionally change due to better inference.
+
+## Non-Goals
+
+- No semantic judge model in this phase.
+- No new acceptance DB schema in this phase.
+- No CLI/gateway rendering changes in this phase.
+- No broad new executable-check runtime beyond what current evaluator already supports.
+
+## Main Risks
+
+1. Over-aggressive splitting may fragment criteria into unusable micro-fragments.
+2. Deliverable inference may become too opinionated and lose important context.
+3. New heuristics may silently regress existing simple-task behavior.
+4. Inferred checks may become too eager and create false failures or inconclusive results.
+
+## Verification Strategy
+
+- Add narrow inference tests first in `tests/agent/test_acceptance.py`.
+- Run only the targeted inference tests in RED/GREEN loops.
+- Then run the full acceptance test file.
+- Finally run a targeted parent-finalizer regression slice to ensure integration behavior did not regress.
